<section id="integration-bigbluebuttonbn">
<h3>BigBlueButton <span class="badge bg-secondary">mod_bigbluebuttonbn</span></h3>

<p>The BBB adapter turns a live-meeting activity into something gradable: a
recording playback area, an <em>Activity Points</em> engagement panel, and
a deep link to BBB's per-attendee Statistics dashboard. Where the
<code>bbbext_advgrd</code> extension is installed, a rubric or marking guide
configured for the activity is rendered in the marking pane the same way
assignment / forum rubrics are.</p>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <strong>Prerequisite for engagement metrics:</strong> the Moodle
    <em>Register live sessions</em> setting (<code>mod_bigbluebuttonbn/meetingevents_enabled</code>)
    must be on, <em>and</em> the BBB server must have <code>defaultKeepEvents=true</code>
    in <code>bbb-web.properties</code>. Without both, BBB never POSTs the analytics
    callback to Moodle and engagement metrics are missing — see <a href="#troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</a>.
    The plugin offers a scraper fallback for when the callback isn't configured;
    that's described below.
</div>

<h4>Recording playback</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Inline iframe</strong> using BBB's playback wrapper URL — the same player you'd see on BBB's recording table.</li>
    <li><strong>Recording switcher</strong> when the activity has multiple recordings: an <em>"All sessions"</em> pill at the start, then one pill per recording (oldest-first, labelled by start time).</li>
    <li><strong>Fullscreen popout</strong> button — requests fullscreen on the outer preview iframe so the player area expands to fill the screen with BBB's controls intact. Works around the nested-iframe permission chain that blocks BBB's own fullscreen control.</li>
    <li><strong>Open in new tab</strong> button next to fullscreen for cases where the embedded player is constrained.</li>
</ul>

<p>When the <code>bbbext_advgrd</code> extension is installed and has overlay
content for the student, its <strong>own-player annotation overlay</strong>
(player + engagement timeline + per-moment comments + an audio/video feedback
callout) renders <em>in place of</em> the BBB iframe. Fullscreen and the rest of
the preview controls still apply — fullscreen targets the overlay's player
wrapper. When the extension isn't installed, or returns nothing for this
student, the view falls back to the standard iframe described above. See
<a href="#plugin-advgrd">bbbext_advgrd</a> for how the integration is wired.</p>

<h4>Activity Points card</h4>
<p>The card shows BBB's engagement breakdown for the current student. It has
two views, toggled by the recording switcher:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>All sessions</strong> (default): cumulative chats, talks, raise-hand events, poll votes, emoji reactions, and total attendance duration across every session the student attended. The <em>Activity Score</em> tile shows BBB's 0-10 composite, averaged across sessions.</li>
    <li><strong>Per-session</strong>: clicking a recording pill loads that recording — the annotation overlay when <code>bbbext_advgrd</code> is installed, otherwise the iframe — <em>and</em> filters the card to that session's metrics with the session's exact Activity Score badge. The pill is the single recording selector: in overlay mode it reloads the preview scoped to that recording (there is no separate dropdown).</li>
</ul>

<p>Sessions match recordings on BBB's internal recording id (the same string
that appears in <code>meta.recordid</code> of an <code>EVENT_SUMMARY</code>
log row, and in <code>local_unifiedgrader_bbbeng.recordingid</code>).
Sessions whose log was recorded but the recording was later deleted from
BBB get a fallback timestamp label.</p>

<h4>Activity Score caveat</h4>
<p>BBB computes the 0-10 Activity Score <em>client-side</em> in its
Statistics playback page — it's not in the meeting-events callback payload.
That means the score appears only when the data has been scraped (see next
section). Sessions whose data came purely from <code>bigbluebuttonbn_logs</code>
won't show a score badge; the rest of the metrics still appear.</p>

<h4>Statistics scraper fallback</h4>
<p>When the BBB analytics callback isn't configured (or is misconfigured),
no <code>EVENT_SUMMARY</code> rows reach Moodle and the engagement card is
empty for everyone. Rather than block grading, the plugin can scrape BBB's
own Statistics playback page server-side:</p>

<ol>
    <li>The teacher clicks <em>"Pull engagement data from BBB recordings"</em> in the engagement-pending warning.</li>
    <li>For each recording, Moodle fetches the <code>statistics</code> playback URL via Moodle's curl wrapper.</li>
    <li>The HTML is parsed (DOMDocument + XPath against the <code>#overview-table</code> and <code>#attention-table</code> sections).</li>
    <li>Participants are matched to Moodle users by normalised fullname.</li>
    <li>Results are cached in <code>local_unifiedgrader_bbbeng</code>, keyed on <code>(cmid, recordingid, userid)</code>.</li>
    <li>The card re-renders, this time with engagement <em>and</em> Activity Score data.</li>
</ol>

<p>Scrape results are visible to the teacher who clicked: matched count,
unmatched count, and total recordings inspected. Unmatched rows land with
<code>userid = 0</code> for manual reconciliation. The button is gated by
the <code>local/unifiedgrader:grade</code> capability.</p>

<h4>"View full analytics" link</h4>
<p>The Activity Points card header carries a button that opens BBB's hosted
Statistics dashboard for the recording in a new tab — full per-attendee
timeline, polls, and engagement breakdown. With multiple recordings the
button becomes a dropdown listing one entry per session.</p>

<h4>Advanced grading via <code>bbbext_advgrd</code></h4>
<p>The companion <code>bbbext_advgrd</code> extension lets you configure a
rubric or marking guide on a BBB activity. When present and configured:</p>

<ul>
    <li>The marking pane renders the rubric / marking guide alongside the standard grade and feedback fields.</li>
    <li>Grades are saved through <code>\bbbext_advgrd\local\grader::record_grade</code> — this writes the per-user evidence snapshot, pushes the score to the gradebook (with optional passthrough), and emits per-presence sub-scores in analytic mode.</li>
    <li>Metric-driven level suggestions (<code>grader::suggest_levels</code>) are passed into the grading definition so rubric cells could be highlighted based on the student's engagement profile.</li>
    <li>The grading instance is reused across saves rather than minted fresh each time, so consecutive saves update the same fillings rather than orphaning prior ones.</li>
    <li>In the preview pane, the extension's own-player annotation overlay replaces the recording iframe when it has content for the student (see <em>Recording playback</em> above).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Attendance status</h4>
<p>A student counts as <em>submitted</em> if they have either an
<code>EVENT_JOIN</code> or an <code>EVENT_SUMMARY</code> log for the
activity, or any cached scrape row. The dual signal handles environments
where the analytics callback isn't wired (you still see attendance from the
JOIN logs Moodle writes itself when a student clicks <em>Join</em>).
Non-attendees show a <em>"Did not attend"</em> badge but remain gradeable.</p>

<h4>Group mode</h4>
<p>BBB tags meetings and recordings with a <code>groupid</code>, and its recording
API filters by the <em>viewer's</em> group. In a <strong>separate-groups</strong>
activity a student (without <em>access all groups</em>) therefore only sees
recordings for their own group, and the switcher lists just those; a grader with
<em>access all groups</em> sees every recording. Engagement data is scoped
per-user regardless of group.</p>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <strong>Student feedback is always reachable
    <span class="badge bg-secondary">v2.7.0</span>.</strong> That group filter
    would otherwise hide the recording a student's annotation feedback lives on
    (a different group, or a <code>groupid&nbsp;0</code> meeting), leaving them
    with no selector and no feedback. So the adapter and the
    <code>bbbext_advgrd</code> overlay additionally surface every recording the
    student has feedback on — looked up by feedback and fetched by recording id,
    which bypasses the group filter — and the student auto-lands on a recording
    that carries their comments. Separate-groups students always see their
    feedback, even when the recording itself sits outside their group.
</div>

